Question: I have a label inside of a div. I want to position the label in the middle of the div and the text on the left side of the label, vertically aligned to center. How can I do this without padding and margin?

<http://jsfiddle.net/E3Wb4/>

```
<div class="center">    
    <label style="width:255px;height:40px;display:inline-block;float:center">Test</label>           
</div>

.center {
padding:0px;
background:#B3B3B3;
height:44px;
width:400px;
border-top:2px solid red;
border-bottom:2px solid red;
border-left:2px solid red;
border-right:2px solid red;
}

label{
    border-top:2px solid yellow;
    border-bottom:2px solid yellow;
    border-left:2px solid yellow;
    border-right:2px solid yellow;
}

```

Answer:

1

To achieve the desired layout where the label is in the middle of the div and the text on the left side of the label, the text is aligned to center without any padding and margin, you can use the following CSS:

```css
.center {
    width: 400px;
    height: 40px;
    background: #B3B3B3;
    padding: 0px;
    margin: 0px;
    display: inline-block; 
    float: center; /* This line aligns the div */
    border-top: 2px solid red;
    border-bottom: 2px solid red;
    border-left: 2px solid red;
    border-right: 2px solid red;
    text-align: center; /* This line centers the text */
}
```

This CSS sets up a container with a specific width and height, a background color, no padding, no margin, displays an inline block (which is the label) that is centered, and has borders as specified. The text-align: center property ensures that the text within the label is aligned to the center.

